1 Introduction & Theoretical Foundations

This module establishes the conceptual and mathematical foundations on which all subsequent mixing-model work rests. By the close of this 30-minute session you should be able to:

  • Describe the physical basis of stable isotope fractionation
  • Explain how trophic enrichment is quantified
  • Discuss tissue-specific isotopic routing
  • Situate dietary isotope analysis within the broader landscape of archaeological science

2 Principles of Stable Isotope Analysis

2.1 What is a Stable Isotope?

Isotopes are atoms of the same element that differ in neutron number and therefore in atomic mass. Stable isotopes do not undergo radioactive decay â unlike the radiogenic 14C exploited in radiocarbon dating, the heavy stable isotopes relevant to dietary reconstruction are permanent constituents of the biosphere.

The two isotope systems used in the vast majority of palaeodietary studies are:

The mass difference of 1 Da in each system is sufficient to produce measurable fractionation at every trophic transfer and biochemical transformation step that involves bond formation or breakage.

2.2 The Delta Notation

Because the absolute abundance of heavy isotopes is very small, isotope ratios are reported as per-mil (â°) deviations from an internationally agreed standard using the delta (Î´) notation:

\[ \delta X\ (\text{â°}) = \left[\frac{R_{\text{sample}}}{R_{\text{standard}}} - 1\right] \times 1000 \tag{1}\]

where \(R\) is the ratio of heavy to light isotope abundance. The internationally agreed reference standards are:

  • Î´13C â Vienna Pee Dee Belemnite (VPDB), a marine carbonate fossil. Values are negative by convention, typically ranging from â35 â° (C3 terrestrial plants) to â7 â° (marine fish).
  • Î´15N â Atmospheric N2 (AIR), defined as 0 â°. Values in biological tissues range from approximately +2 â° (legumes with N2-fixation symbiosis) to +20 â° or higher in apex marine predators.
Key interpretive rule

A more positive Î´13C value indicates incorporation of marine or C4-plant carbon. A more positive Î´15N value indicates a higher trophic position, or consumption of manured or marine-derived protein.

2.3 Analytical Measurement

Stable isotope ratios are measured by Isotope Ratio Mass Spectrometry (IRMS). In continuous-flow configurations (CF-IRMS), sample combustion and introduction to the mass spectrometer are integrated, enabling high-throughput analysis from as little as 0.3â1.0 mg of collagen. Typical analytical precision is Â±0.1â0.2 â° (1Ï) for both Î´13C and Î´15N â sufficient to resolve trophic-level differences, which are typically 3â5 â° per level for nitrogen.

2.4 The Î´Â¹Â³C / Î´Â¹âµN Biplot

The most common visualisation in palaeodietary isotope work is the two-dimensional isotope biplot, which places individuals or populations within a reference space defined by food-web end-members.

Human groups (grey open circles) sit above their dietary end-members by approximately one trophic step for Î´15N (~+4 â°) and close to or slightly above diet for Î´13C (~+1 â°), reflecting trophic enrichment factors discussed in SectionÂ 3.

Summary: Why Î´Â¹Â³C and Î´Â¹âµN?
  • Î´13C discriminates between C3 and C4 plant consumers, and between terrestrial and marine protein sources.
  • Î´15N tracks trophic level: each step up the food chain enriches 15N by ~3â5 â°.
  • Together, they place individuals in a 2-dimensional isotope space reflecting the main axes of dietary variation.
  • Both can be measured simultaneously on a single IRMS run from a few milligrams of collagen.

3 Isotopic Fractionation and Trophic Level Effects

3.1 What is Fractionation?

Isotopic fractionation describes any process that alters the heavy-to-light isotope ratio of a substance relative to its source. Two categories are relevant:

Equilibrium fractionation
Arises from thermodynamic differences in bond energies involving isotopically distinct molecules. It is temperature-dependent and is the primary driver of 13C partitioning during carbonate precipitation.
Kinetic fractionation
Arises when lighter isotopologues react faster than heavier ones. Biological enzyme-catalysed reactions â photosynthesis, transamination, deamination â are dominated by kinetic effects.

3.2 Trophic Enrichment Factors (TEFs)

When an organism synthesises tissue from dietary protein and energy substrates, fractionation at each biochemical step produces systematic isotopic enrichment relative to diet. These offsets are called Trophic Enrichment Factors (TEFs) or discrimination factors, denoted Î (capital delta):

\[ \Delta^{13}C = \delta^{13}C_{\text{tissue}} - \delta^{13}C_{\text{diet}} \tag{2}\]

\[ \Delta^{15}N = \delta^{15}N_{\text{tissue}} - \delta^{15}N_{\text{diet}} \tag{3}\]

Published TEF estimates for human bone collagen vary considerably (TableÂ 2). This variation is a major source of uncertainty in mixing models and must be propagated explicitly.

Critical caveat on TEF values

TEF values are not universal constants. They vary with tissue type, metabolic state, protein quality, and potentially with latitude and season. When constructing a mixing model, always justify your TEF choice and propagate its uncertainty using the standard deviation reported in your chosen source. Sensitivity analyses using alternative TEF values are strongly recommended before drawing dietary conclusions.

3.3 The Trophic Step Effect on Î´Â¹âµN

The approximately 3â5 â° enrichment in Î´15N per trophic level arises because:

  1. Dietary amino acids undergo transamination and deamination; 14N-bearing compounds are preferentially excreted as urea or ammonia.
  2. The heavier 15N is therefore retained and concentrated in somatic protein.
  3. With each successive trophic transfer the cumulative enrichment compounds, producing a predictable ladder of Î´15N values through the food web.

Archaeological confounders of Î´Â¹âµN

Elevated Î´15N is not always diagnostic of high-status meat consumption:

  • Manured soils elevate baseline plant Î´15N, cascading up the food web
  • Breastfed neonates show apparent trophic elevation (~+2â3 â°) relative to their mothers
  • Physiological stress (starvation, illness) can increase tissue Î´15N through net protein catabolism
  • Arid environments tend to have systematically elevated Î´15N baselines throughout the ecosystem

4 Isotopic Routing and Tissue-Specific Considerations

4.1 What is Isotopic Routing?

Isotopic routing refers to the differential biochemical fate of dietary macronutrients â proteins, lipids, and carbohydrates â during tissue synthesis. It has profound implications for interpreting collagen isotope data and for constructing mixing models, because collagen does not reflect bulk diet uniformly across all macronutrient classes.

4.2 Carbon Routing to Bone Collagen

Bone collagen is synthesised almost entirely from amino acids, and these are preferentially sourced from dietary protein rather than from carbohydrates or lipids. Key experimental findings include:

  • Dietary protein carbon contributes disproportionately to collagen carbon (~60â80 % in controlled-diet studies; Ambrose & Norr 1993).
  • Dietary carbohydrate and lipid carbon contribute relatively little to collagen, even when they represent the majority of caloric intake.
  • Bone collagen Î´13C is therefore a better proxy for dietary protein source than for total diet isotopic composition.

Practical consequence: end-member isotope values in a collagen-based mixing model should reflect the protein-derived isotopic signal from each food source, not the bulk food Î´13C. This issue is especially acute for protein-poor, high-carbohydrate diets (e.g., millet- or maize-dependent farming communities).

4.3 Carbonate Apatite as a Complementary Proxy

The carbonate fraction of bone mineral (bioapatite) reflects whole-diet carbon, because carbon from all dietary macronutrients can be incorporated into bone apatite via bicarbonate in blood.

Diagenesis and apatite Î´Â¹Â³C

Bone carbonate is extremely susceptible to post-mortem exchange with groundwater carbonates. The apatite Î´13C and Î´18O values of archaeological specimens must be screened for diagenetic alteration (e.g., using crystallinity index, %C, or FTIR analysis) before inclusion in mixing models. In practice, apatite data from waterlogged or chemically active burial environments are often unusable.

4.4 Tissue Turnover Rates

Different tissues record dietary signals over different timescales, because they undergo metabolic turnover at different rates. This concept is directly analogous to the integration window familiar from radiocarbon dating.

For most archaeological applications, bone collagen is the primary substrate. However, comparing adult bone collagen with dentine collagen from the same individual can provide a longitudinal perspective on dietary change across the life course â a valuable tool for studying weaning, migration, and social transitions.

5.2 Research Questions Addressed by Isotope Mixing Models

Relevance to radiocarbon practitioners

Stable isotope data are routinely collected from specimens submitted for 14C dating. The Î´13C value used to correct for isotopic fractionation in AMS dating is measured on the same collagen extract, providing an incidental dietary signal.

High marine protein intake (elevated Î´13C and Î´15N) is directly implicated in the Marine Reservoir Effect, which can cause apparent age offsets of several centuries if unaccounted for. Mixing-model dietary estimates are increasingly used to quantify the proportion of marine protein in diet and thereby calculate a site-specific 14C offset (ÎR correction).

5.3 Collagen Quality Assessment

Before any mixing model can be constructed, the quality and integrity of the collagen extract must be assessed. Degraded collagen introduces systematic bias because isotope ratios shift with diagenetic alteration.

Specimens failing these criteria should be excluded from mixing-model datasets or treated as having substantially inflated uncertainty. In practice, the C:N ratio is the most widely used single criterion.
